modules.name: AWS.DMS
modules.comments:
AWS Database Migration Service

AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) can migrate your data to and from the most widely used commercial and open-source databases such as Oracle, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Amazon Redshift, MariaDB, Amazon Aurora, MySQL, and SAP Adaptive Server Enterprise (ASE). The service supports homogeneous migrations such as Oracle to Oracle, as well as heterogeneous migrations between different database platforms, such as Oracle to MySQL or SQL Server to PostgreSQL.

For more information about AWS DMS, see the AWS DMS user guide at What Is AWS Database Migration Service?

declarations.comments: Adds metadata tags to a DMS resource, including replication instance, endpoint, security group, and migration task. These tags can also be used with cost allocation reporting to track cost associated with DMS resources, or used in a Condition statement in an IAM policy for DMS.
declarations.title: addTagsToResource

declarations.comments: Creates an endpoint using the provided settings.
declarations.title: createEndpoint

declarations.comments:
Creates an AWS DMS event notification subscription.

You can specify the type of source (SourceType) you want to be notified of, provide a list of AWS DMS source IDs (SourceIds) that triggers the events, and provide a list of event categories (EventCategories) for events you want to be notified of. If you specify both the SourceType and SourceIds, such as SourceType = replication-instance and SourceIdentifier = my-replinstance, you will be notified of all the replication instance events for the specified source. If you specify a SourceType but don't specify a SourceIdentifier, you receive notice of the events for that source type for all your AWS DMS sources. If you don't specify either SourceType nor SourceIdentifier, you will be notified of events generated from all AWS DMS sources belonging to your customer account.

For more information about AWS DMS events, see Working with Events and Notifications in the AWS Database MIgration Service User Guide.
declarations.title: createEventSubscription

declarations.comments: Creates the replication instance using the specified parameters.
declarations.title: createReplicationInstance

declarations.comments: Creates a replication subnet group given a list of the subnet IDs in a VPC.
declarations.title: createReplicationSubnetGroup

declarations.comments: Creates a replication task using the specified parameters.
declarations.title: createReplicationTask

declarations.comments:
Deletes the specified endpoint.

All tasks associated with the endpoint must be deleted before you can delete the endpoint.
declarations.title: deleteEndpoint

declarations.comments: Deletes an AWS DMS event subscription.
declarations.title: deleteEventSubscription

declarations.comments:
Deletes the specified replication instance.

You must delete any migration tasks that are associated with the replication instance before you can delete it.
declarations.title: deleteReplicationInstance

declarations.comments:
Lists all of the AWS DMS attributes for a customer account. The attributes include AWS DMS quotas for the account, such as the number of replication instances allowed. The description for a quota includes the quota name, current usage toward that quota, and the quota's maximum value.

This command does not take any parameters.
declarations.title: describeAccountAttributes

declarations.comments: Describes the status of the connections that have been made between the replication instance and an endpoint. Connections are created when you test an endpoint.
declarations.title: describeConnections

declarations.comments: Returns information about the type of endpoints available.
declarations.title: describeEndpointTypes

declarations.comments: Returns information about the endpoints for your account in the current region.
declarations.title: describeEndpoints

declarations.comments: Lists categories for all event source types, or, if specified, for a specified source type. You can see a list of the event categories and source types in Working with Events and Notifications in the AWS Database Migration Service User Guide.
declarations.title: describeEventCategories

declarations.comments:
Lists all the event subscriptions for a customer account. The description of a subscription includes SubscriptionName, SNSTopicARN, CustomerID, SourceType, SourceID, CreationTime, and Status.

If you specify SubscriptionName, this action lists the description for that subscription.
declarations.title: describeEventSubscriptions

declarations.comments: Lists events for a given source identifier and source type. You can also specify a start and end time. For more information on AWS DMS events, see Working with Events and Notifications .
declarations.title: describeEvents

declarations.comments: Returns information about the replication instance types that can be created in the specified region.
declarations.title: describeOrderableReplicationInstances

declarations.comments: Returns the status of the RefreshSchemas operation.
declarations.title: describeRefreshSchemasStatus

declarations.comments: Returns information about the task logs for the specified task.
declarations.title: describeReplicationInstanceTaskLogs

declarations.comments: Returns information about replication instances for your account in the current region.
declarations.title: describeReplicationInstances

declarations.comments: Returns information about the replication subnet groups.
declarations.title: describeReplicationSubnetGroups

declarations.comments: Returns the task assessment results from Amazon S3. This action always returns the latest results.
declarations.title: describeReplicationTaskAssessmentResults

declarations.comments: Returns information about replication tasks for your account in the current region.
declarations.title: describeReplicationTasks

declarations.comments: Returns information about the schema for the specified endpoint.
declarations.title: describeSchemas

declarations.comments:
Returns table statistics on the database migration task, including table name, rows inserted, rows updated, and rows deleted.

Note that the "last updated" column the DMS console only indicates the time that AWS DMS last updated the table statistics record for a table. It does not indicate the time of the last update to the table.
declarations.title: describeTableStatistics

declarations.comments: Lists all tags for an AWS DMS resource.
declarations.title: listTagsForResource

declarations.comments: Modifies an existing AWS DMS event notification subscription.
declarations.title: modifyEventSubscription

declarations.comments:
Modifies the replication instance to apply new settings. You can change one or more parameters by specifying these parameters and the new values in the request.

Some settings are applied during the maintenance window.
declarations.title: modifyReplicationInstance

declarations.comments: Modifies the settings for the specified replication subnet group.
declarations.title: modifyReplicationSubnetGroup

declarations.comments:
Modifies the specified replication task.

You can't modify the task endpoints. The task must be stopped before you can modify it.

For more information about AWS DMS tasks, see the AWS DMS user guide at Working with Migration Tasks
declarations.title: modifyReplicationTask

declarations.comments: Reboots a replication instance. Rebooting results in a momentary outage, until the replication instance becomes available again.
declarations.title: rebootReplicationInstance

declarations.comments: Populates the schema for the specified endpoint. This is an asynchronous operation and can take several minutes. You can check the status of this operation by calling the DescribeRefreshSchemasStatus operation.
declarations.title: refreshSchemas

declarations.comments: Reloads the target database table with the source data.
declarations.title: reloadTables

declarations.comments: Removes metadata tags from a DMS resource.
declarations.title: removeTagsFromResource

declarations.comments:
Starts the replication task.

For more information about AWS DMS tasks, see the AWS DMS user guide at Working with Migration Tasks
declarations.title: startReplicationTask

declarations.comments: Starts the replication task assessment for unsupported data types in the source database.
declarations.title: startReplicationTaskAssessment

declarations.comments: Tests the connection between the replication instance and the endpoint.
declarations.title: testConnection

declarations.comments: AWS DMS was denied access to the endpoint.
declarations.title: AccessDeniedFault

declarations.comments: Describes a quota for an AWS account, for example, the number of replication instances allowed.
declarations.title: AccountQuota

declarations.comments: The SSL certificate that can be used to encrypt connections between the endpoints and the replication instance.
declarations.title: Certificate

declarations.comments: There are not enough resources allocated to the database migration.
declarations.title: InsufficientResourceCapacityFault

declarations.comments: The resource is in a state that prevents it from being used for database migration.
declarations.title: InvalidResourceStateFault

declarations.comments: AWS DMS cannot access the KMS key.
declarations.title: KMSKeyNotAccessibleFault

declarations.comments: Contains metadata for a replication instance task log.
declarations.title: ReplicationInstanceTaskLog

declarations.comments: The replication subnet group does not cover enough Availability Zones (AZs). Edit the replication subnet group and add more AZs.
declarations.title: ReplicationSubnetGroupDoesNotCoverEnoughAZs

declarations.comments: The task assessment report in JSON format.
declarations.title: ReplicationTaskAssessmentResult

declarations.comments: The resource you are attempting to create already exists.
declarations.title: ResourceAlreadyExistsFault

declarations.comments: The quota for this resource quota has been exceeded.
declarations.title: ResourceQuotaExceededFault

declarations.comments: You are not authorized for the SNS subscription.
declarations.title: SNSNoAuthorizationFault

declarations.comments: The specified subnet is already in use.
declarations.title: SubnetAlreadyInUse

declarations.comments: An upgrade dependency is preventing the database migration.
declarations.title: UpgradeDependencyFailureFault
